[ctns_demo flashcard]

[ctns_make id='QF-QuadraticFormula']

    [ctns_front]
The Quadratic Formula
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
Given a quadratic function in general form

$|ax^2 + bx + c = 0,|$

then the solutions are
$|x=\frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}|$
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
The solution to the quadratic formula is the value

x equals negative b -- plus or minus the square root of b-squared minus 4--a--c -- all divided by 2--a.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]




[ctns_make id='QF-QuadraticFunctionGeneralForm']

    [ctns_front]
Quadratic Function<br/>General Form
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
A quadratic function is a function that can
be written in the form

$|y = ax^2 + bx + c,|$

where $$a$$, $$b$$, and $$c$$ are constants and $$a \ne 0$$.
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
A quadratic function is a function that can
be written in the form

y equals -- a -- times x squared plus -- b -- times x plus -- c --,

where -- a --, -- b --, and -- c -- are constants and -- a -- not equal to zero.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]





[ctns_make id='QF-QuadraticFunctionVertexForm']

    [ctns_front]
Quadratic Function<br/>Vertex Form
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
A quadratic function can be written
in the form

$|y -k = a(x - h)^2,|$

where $$a$$, $$h$$, and $$k$$ are constants, $$a \ne 0,$$, and the vertex is the point $$(h,k)$$.
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
A quadratic function can be written
in the form

y minus k equals -- a -- times the difference squared of x minus h,

where -- a --, -- h --, and -- k -- are constants, -- a -- not equal to zero, and the vertex is the point -- h -- k.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]





[ctns_make id='QF-TheDiscriminant' flush]

    [ctns_front]
Discriminant
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
Given a quadratic function in general form,

$|ax^2 + bx + c = 0,|$

the discriminant is the expression

$|b^2 - 4 a c|$
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
Given a quadratic function in general form

a -- times x squared plus b -- times x -- plus c equals zero

then the discriminant is the expression

b squared minus 4--a--c.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]




[ctns_make id='QF-Parabola']

    [ctns_front]
Parabola
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
A <strong>parabola</strong> is the set of all 
points $$(x,y)$$ in a plane that are equidistant to a fixed point (focus) and to a line (directrix).

$|
\begin{aligned}
(x-h)^2 = 4p(y-k) \\
(y-h)^2 = 4p(x-k)
\end{aligned}
|$
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
A parabola is the set of all 
points in a plane that are equidistant to a fixed point -- the focus 
-- and a line -- the directrix.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='QF-Circle']

    [ctns_front]
Circle
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
A <strong>circle</strong> is the set of all 
points $$(x,y)$$ in a plane at a fixed distance $$r$$ from a fixed point $$(h,k)$$, where $$r$$ is the radius of the circle and $$(h,k)$$ the center.

$|(x-h)^2 +(y-k)^2 = r^2|$
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
A circle is the set of all points in
a plane at a fixed distance from a fixed point, where
the fixed distance is the radius of the circle and the fixed point the center.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]



[ctns_make id='QF-VertexOfAParabola']

    [ctns_front]
Vertex of a parabola
    [/ctns_front]

    [ctns_back style='width:80%;font-size:90%;']
Given a quadratic function in general form

$|f(x) = ax^2+bx+c=0|$

the vertex is given by the point

$| (\frac{-b}{2a}, f(\frac{-b}{2a}))|$
    [/ctns_back]

    [ctns_backspeak]
Given a quadratic function in general form

f of x equals -- a times x squared plus b 
times x plus c equals zero --

the vertex is given by the point

x equals negative b divided by -- 2 -- a, and y equals
f of negative b divided by -- 2 -- a.
    [/ctns_backspeak]

[/ctns_make]

[/ctns_demo]